{"/service/ndnp/mthi/batch_mthi_clarkia_ver01/data/sn84036287/00340581830/1938010701/0005.xml":{"full_text":"PAGE TOUR\nCarbon County News\nO. H. P. SHELLEY, Editor and Owner\nPublished every Friday at Red Lodge. Carbon Co., Montana\nMatter of\nEntered at the Postoffice at Red Lodge, Montana, as\nSecond Class, under the Act of Congress of March \u00f6. isva.\nSubscription\u2014Per year. $2.60; six months, $1.50; three months.\n$.75. All subscriptioas payable in advance.\nOFFICIAL PAPER OF CARBON COUNTY\nAND CITY OF BED LODGE\nTELEPHONE NUMBER NINE\nTHE NEW YEAR BEGINS\nThe American people are entering the New Year in a\nfar different mood than the one which enveloped us\ntwelve months ago. Then we were apparently prosperous\nand at peace with the world. Corporations were vying with\none another in granting extra dividends and bonuses. Un\nemployment seemed to be steadily decreasing just as bus\niness was continually climbing,\nto feel that we were in danger of becoming involved in a\ncritical way with any foreign power. Politically we seem\ned to have entered another era of good feeling.\nBut the unfolding of the year 1937 brought a decided\nchange. Labor troubles followed one another in rapid suc\ncession, taxes mounted, and business instead of continuing\nto climb, began to level off and then to start a decline. The\nstock market, hesitated, halted, and then put on one of the\nsharpest and severest declines in the history of the ex\nchange.\nThe sudden attack of Japan on China and the resultant\nbombing of American ships, and the sinking of a gunboat\nwith loss of life, broug'ht us into the midst of an interna\ntional crisis which has not yet been solved.\nThe political era of good feeling was disrupted by the\nlong fight in Congress over the proposal of the President\nThere seemed no reason\nto make over the Supreme Court. Following this came the\nspecial session of Congress which failed to accomplish the\nwork set out for it, and resulted among other things, in\nthe emasculation and defeat of the President's pet wages\nand hours bill.\nAt the beginning of 1938, therefore, the American peo\nple are confronted with an entirely different set of prob\nlems than the one they had to face at the beginning of\n1937. It is admitted that we are in a business recession.\nJust what that means nobody at this moment can tell.\nEveryone hopes that the recession will be short lived and\nthat we will soon again take up the march toward normal\ncy, just as he fervently expresses the wish that our foreign\ntroubles can be settled honorably and peacefully.\nThis is no time for gloom spreading. Already there are\nsigns of returning sanity in the solution of many of our\neconomic difficulties\u2014signs that the days of roseate ex\nperimentation are about over and sooner than anticipat\ned we mil get back on solid ground again. In all efforts\nto end the recession and solve our foreign problems in an\nAmerican way, the administration will, of course, have\nthe support of the American people. But the period of\nblind following in domestic economic and social experi\nmentation seems about ended. That is one of the hopeful\nsigns for the beginning of 1938.\nMussolini says he thinks that Germany ought to have some colonies.\nWell, how about Sicily or a slice of Ethiopia?\nThose New Yorkers are certainly ambitious. It is said now that they\nplan to erect a skyscraper as high as the national debt.\nBETTER WAYS TO SAVE\nPresident Roosevelt lias recommended, as an economy\nthat federal funds for highway construction be\nmeasure,\nreduced to amounts comparable with those of the prede\npression years. He further asks cacellation of an author\nization of $214,000,000 for the 1939 road program which\nthe secretary of agriculture normally would allocate to the\nvarious states by the first of next year.\nEncouraging as it is to find the president thinking in\nterms of economy after an orgy of government spending,\nfail to see much merit or soundness in this gesture of\nsaving. There are better ways to attain larger and more\nsensible economics. The president has only to take note of\nthe numerous money-spending agencies and bureaus that\nhave been created during his administration to know that\nthis is true. He has the opportunity to accomplish, or at\nleast advocate, the abolishment of overlapping and dupli\ncating governmental functions and the only injury in so\ndoing would be a partial demobilization of the great army\nof employes that has its hand in the federal treasury.\nLikewise there is opportunity to halt the flow of funds\ngoing to the great experimenters whose main achievement\nhas been the development of an enormous capacity to\nspend.\nHighway building is not an experiment. The business\nof constructing roads has served the great purpose of\nbringing all sections of this vast country into closer con\ntact. It has been a boon to the evergrowing motoring pub\nlic. It has kept thousands of men at work and millions of\ndollars worth of equipment from idleness and if the presi\ndent is really desirous of seeing substantial and perman\nent improvements made with the additional advantage of\npartially relieving the unemployment problem, he ought\nnot to urge curtailment of an essential activity like high\nway construction.\nBecause of the vastness of our country, there is much\nroad building yet to be done and wisdom argues against\npermitting it to lag. Particularly is this true in most of\nwestern states where large areas are still without the\nadvantages of serviceable roads. It will be the west that\nwill suffer most should the congress decide to carry out\nthe president's plan for a\nshortsighted. Happily most western members of congress,\nirrespective of party, are lining up in opposition to the\nrecommendation.\nWC\nmil\nsaving that is as small as it is\nLet the president forget about his Quoddies, his seven\nlittle TVA 's and any number of other schemes that run\ninto real money, and help preserve the strength and ef\nfectiveness of a government and state partnership that has\ntaken America somewhere and not to dead ends.\u2014Billings\nGazette.\n\nIt is said that a split is threatened now in the Republican Party.\nWhat it is going to be be, Maine vs. Vermont?\nMACHINE IN REVERSE\nDuring the first New Deal administration wo were told\nthat prices were too low but that they would be increased\nin one way or another\u2014hence the laws for restricting pro\nduction and devaluing the dollar. Now we are told that\nprices are too high and that something must be done to\nreduce costs so that we can wage a tremendous housing\nprogram to stop the crying of the new \"baby\" depression.\nA year or so ago we were told that a surplus profits tax\nthe thing to inaugurate, to reduce taxes and make big\nbusiness divide up with the common people. Now we arc\ninformed that this surplus profits tax must be repealed in\norder to give business a chance to defeat the new business\nrecession.\nFor years we have been regaled with the story that the\nway to\" get a new prosperity was to prime the pump with\ntremendous business expenditure, that an increase in.the\npublic debt was immaterial in light of the objectives to be\ngained. Now we are being told that expenses must be trim\nmed and the budget balanced, and the President suggests\nwe start in by curtailing federal funds for road building.\nEvidently the New Deal machine is going into reverse\ngear. \"What is the matter anyhow? If we planned this way,\nafter five long years what is the use of changing every\nthing by \"un -planning\nwas\nit?\n\nBrazil has learned after years of experience that it is impossible for\nthe government to control coffee production. Henry Wallace hasn't had\nmuch experience but if we are patient and give him ime he'll learn,\nas\ntoo.\nkogram For Week At\nThe Roman Theatre\nFri. Sat., Jan. 7-8. RAINBOW\nNITE SATURDAY! JEAN PAR\nKER, LEO CARRILLO, JAMES\nELLISON in REX BEACH'S \"THE\nBARRIER\". Between this man and\nwoman was a barrier only a great\nlove could break! Gold-mad Yukon\ndays live again in pulse-pounding\naction and surging romance, a\ngainst a background of awe-inspir\ning beauty in the great North\nCountry! Added:\nED STALLION\nNews! Shows 7 9! PAL NITE\nFRIDAY!\nSun. Mon. Tues., Jan. 9-10-11.\nThe throbbing story of a wife who\nlied, and lied, and lied! CAROLE\nLOMBARD, FRED MacMURRAY,\nJOHN BARRYMORE in \"TRUE\nCONFESSION\". They're on ano\nther bender in the dizziest, daf\nfiest comedy hit of the Year; Add\ned: Comedy, Popeye Cartoon,\nNews!\nWED., THURS., Jan. 12-13.\nRAINBOW NITE WEDNESDAY!\n'THE PAINT\nNo. 4 Fox\n\nDouble Features: No. 1 WILL\nROGERS in IRVIN S. COBB'S\n\"JUDGE PRIEST,\" with Rochelle\nHudson, Tom Brown. Tempering\njustice with kindness, salting kind\nness with wit, chuckling his way\ninto your heart, in the most warm\nly human picture he ever made!\nNo. 2. DICK FORAN in \"BLAZ\nING SIXES.\" A knockout MYS\nTERY WESTERN! Added: Com\nedy! PAL NITE THURSDAY!\nComing! Sun. Mon. Tues., Jan.\n16-17-18. LORETTA YOUNG,\nWARNER BAXTER, VIRGINIA\nBRUCE in \"WIFE, DOCTOR AND\nNURSE.\" For every wife whose\nhusband works with other women;\nfor every girl whose boss is hand\nsome,\u2014and married Sparkling,\nwitty romance in the mood of to\nday!\nCARBON RALLIES\n(Continued from Page 1)\nthat may prove dangerous when\nmid-season form is reached.\nBelfry fought hard all the way\nand deserves credit for gameness.\nIn A. Brown, Bat guard, the home\nclub displayed a nice performer.\nBrown easily led his team\nseven points, and got two of Bel\nfry's three field goals.\nwith\nUndefeat ed in Tri-county\nleague play as yet, Red Lodge\nfaces some tough games in the\nnext week. Tonight Park City\nplays at Washington hall in what\nshould be a fast contest. Saturday\nthe Hartwigmen trek to Bearcreek\ntossup melee. Next week the\nin a\nboys start off with Fromberg at\nFromberg on Tuesday night. In\ncontest which should go a long\ntowards determining the\na\nway\nleague championship, Laurel's im\npressive five will clash with the\nlocals here next Thursday night,\nJan. 13. Roundup, the state class\nB champions which administered\na beating to Carbon here a few\nweeks ago, will be host to the Red\nLodge aggregation a week from\ntonight, Jan. 14.\nSTATE BUYS BONDS\nMrs. N. B. Sherlock\ncommis\nsioner of lands and investments, in\nvested $7,000 in 20-year 5 per cent\nRoosevelt county school bonds and\n$2,850 in 10-year school bonds of\nHill county bearing 5 per cent, this\nweek.\nNAMED ATTORNEY\nWarren Toole of Great Fklls\nwas named attorney for the Liquor\nControl Board it was announced\nlast week by Administrator L. M.\nA. Waas. He also takes over the\nduties of James J. Brett as assis\ntant administrator. Son of Mon\ntana's first governor, Attorney\nToole has been acting as chief\ncounsel for the State Highway de\npartment since last April. He is a\nresident of Great Falls and has\nbeen twice city attorney there. He\nserved on the State Supreme Court\nbench in 1926. Mr. Toole was born\nin Helena during the term of his\nfather Joseph K. Toole as gover\nnor.\nWAITING FDR OKEH\nJobs for 069 drouth victims and\nconstruction work on irrigation\nprojects started by WPA in four\ncounties await the approval of\nPresident Roosevelt, the State\nWater Board informed Governor\nRoy E. Ayers this week.\nThe projects were launched by the\nState W. P. A. but the men were\nlaid off when it was discovered\npresidential approval of the jobs\nAyers wired 'Senator Murray seek\ning aid in getting the projects ap\nproved. The jobs consist of dams\nin Richland, Dawson, Custer and\nFallon counties. WPA is furnish\ning the labor and equipment and\nthe Water board the engineering.\nThe projects are a part of the\nBoard's plan to rehabilitate the\ndrouth areas, Chief Engineer E. B.\nDonohue announced.\nSTAR MEAT FIVE,\nSAWYERS IN WIN\nWith McGuire leading his team\nwith 12 points, Sawyers edged out\nSafeway 's quintet in a city league\nbasketball game Tuesday night,\n34 to 26. In the other game Star\nMeat's improving five downed the\nMiller Drug, 38 to 21.\nOther scorers on the winning\nSawyer aggregation are M. Ny\nback, 4; A. Dimich, 6; Vibetto, 6;\nSekulich, 4 and Cheadle, 2.\nFor Safeways, J. Doran and C.\nJarvi each scored 8 points. Other\ncounters were Obert, 5; Cover, 2;\nand M. Dimich, 3.\nO. Nyback and J. Krop paced\nthe winning butchers, each snag\nging 10 points. They were closely\nfollowed by S. Krop with 9 tallies\nand Niemi with 8.\n\nMiheheh was high on the losing\ndruggists with 8 points, followed\nby Kola, 5; Landers, 4, and Koski\nand Berta, 2 each,\nBASEBALL PICTURE\n\"Batter Up,\" the fourth official\nsound motion picture to be pro-'\nduced by the American League in\ncooperation with the Fisher Body\ndivision of General Motors, will be\nreleased in January following a\nseries of previews in the eight\nLeague cities, President Will Har\nridge disclosed today. Entirely\nnew, the film was written and di\nrected by Lew Fonseca, director\nof promotion for the league, with\nTed Husing doing the narration.\nIt will be distributed free of\ncharge by the body-building divi\nsion of the automotive concern.\nHarry Huchins,\nLina Luoma,\nEdward Luoma and Bill Luoma\nmotored to Cody, Wyo., last week\non business.\n-a\n\nshots\nkyjAMES Preston\nV;\nThe so-called \"coalition\" in the\nSenate has caused more surprises\nthan one. And it begins to look as\nthough it will cause plenty more.\nIn the first place, premature\npublicity on such a thing usually\ndoes much to stop it. That would\nhave been more true in this in\nstance if the coalitionists had\nbeen attempting to obtain signa\ntures on the dotted line. But de\nspite what has been written to that\neffect, the backers of the now fam\nous 10-point program put it for\nfard only as something that might\nbe a yardstick in helping Senators\ndetermine their stand on various\npublic questions.\nThe fact is that the publicity did\nnot hurt the coalitionists at all. It\nsimply enabled them to say public\nly what they were saying private\nly. And newspapermen, once the\nthing reached the stage of public\ndebate, were impressed with the\nsincerity of those who support the\nplan.\nAs a matter of fact, the 10\npoint program was the kind of a\nprogram which almost any legis\nlator\u2014except one with socialistic\nor collectivistic tendencies\naccept and approve. In short, it\nwas just another way of stating\nthings which are accepted by all\nwho believe in a Constitutional,\ndemocratic form of government,\nregjardless of their political tie\nould\nups.\nIncidentally, the program as\nproposed the coalitionists\nnot far different than that adopted\na few weeks before in New York\nby the nation's manufacturers at\nthe Congress of American Indus\ntry. The Senate program called for:\nTax revision; steps toward a bal\nanced budget; impartiality by gov\nernment if it is forced into em\nployer-employee relationship; eli\nmination or limitation of govern\nment competition in private enter\nprise; maintenance of competition\nrather than monopoly; stabiliza\ntion of values; assurance that\ntaxes will not be increased; recog\nnition of state rights; ample relief\neconomically administered, and\npreservation of the American sys\ntem of private enterprise and ini\ntiative.\nOne thing sure, the \"coalition\"\nprogram has not been side-tracked.\nIts progress has been slowed but\nthe last has not yet been heard of\nit\u2014by far.\nDespite the remarkable defeat\ndealt the wage-hour bill during the\nspecial session of Congress, folks\nalready are beating the bushes to\nfind out how some such legislation\ncan be put through the regular\nsession.\nSome Washington officials hope\nthat while the Congressmen were\nback home they found public senti\nment to be strongly in favor of the\nlegislation. But others remember\nthat Congressmen were supposed,\nduring the recess between the regu\nlar and special sessions, to get all\npepped up about the administra\ntion's legislative program and\npush it through. Instead, Congress\ncontinued to follow the policy of\nmaking its own decisions. And al\nthough it advanced much legisla\ntion, it refused to simply write\n\"O.K.\" on anything.\nThe astounding thing about the\nwage-hour fight is nobody can find\nout who really wants it. Congress\ndoesn't, industry doesn't, and the\ntwo leading labor organizations\nare far from enthusiastic about it.\nYet the proposal lives on and on.\nCarbon Lovers\nFrown On June\nFor Marrying\ni\ni\nFor some reason or other pros\npective newlyweds last year\nchewed purchasing Carbon county\nmarriage licenses in June, suppos\ned to be the big month for wedd\nes\nmgs.\nC. P. Larkin, clerk of district\ncourt, announced that only two\nmonths had fewer marriage lic\nenses than June, when six couples\napplied. Lovers favored July,\nwhich contributed 23 towards the\nyear's total of 125. There were 20\ndivorces during 1937. Marriage\nlicenses issued compare favorably\nwith 1936 when 128 were taken\nout.\nMonth-by-month record of per\nmits and divorces, number of lic\nenses given first is as follows:\nJanuary, eight and one; February,\ntwo and none; March, 10 and two;\nApril, eight and one; May, 13 and\nthree; June, six and two; July, 23\nand none; August, 14 and 1; Sep\ntember, 13 and one; October, 10\nand none; November, 13 and four,\nand December, five and five.\nBECKETT IS NAMED\nE. J. Beckett of Missoula was\nnamed deputy state examiner by\nW. A. Brown, state examiner this\nweek, filling a vacancy. Mr. Beck\nett, a democrat, was formerly\ncounty treasurer at Missoula coun\nty, and has been serving as deputy\ncounty clerk under W. J. Babing\nton.\nDRUGS DISCUSSED\n(Continued from Page 1)\nprogram on Legislation. Mrs.\nField discussed: The Pure Food\nand Drug Act and proposed\namendments; registration of fire\narms and ownership of same; de\nportation of alien criminals; uni\nform state traffic laws, and high\nway safety provisions; a national\nschool for training of men and\nwomen for government service;\nstate memorial forests by state\nfederations of women's clubs-, and\nprotection of national forests from\ncommercial agencies.\nMrs. McFate discussed the need\nfor uniform narcotic laws, and\nread a very informative article on\nthe dangers lurking in the Mari\nhuana weed (loco weed) being\nmade into cigarettes and distrib\nuted through illicit channels of\ntrade. Insanity being the compar\natively early result of the use of\nMarihuana, the states should recog\nnize the economic disadvantage of\nproviding institutional care for\nvictims of this American grown\nnarcotic. Legal condemnation and\ndestruction of this crop demands\nlegislation\u2014uniform legislation\u2014\nin all States of the Union. Other\nNarcotic laws need to be made uni\nform in all States, as well. The\nnext general session program will\nbe on International Relations.\nThe business session preceded\nthe program. Reports were given\nby Mesdames Brophy, Field and\nSpogen.\nMrs. Brophy gave her annual\nreport on the Philanthropic De\npartment's work for the Associat\ned Charities of the town. Mrs.\nField reports an unusually good\nresponse to the .Seal Sale which\nfund will be required to help pay\nin the high schools of Carbon Coun\nty thru services of the Field Nurse,\nMiss Leila McDonald, of the Mon\ntana Tuberculosis Association,\nwhose salary is paid by this As\nsociation, and the X-ray pictures\nwhich also are paid by the Assoc\niation.\nDr. B. K. Kilbourne, Epidemiol\nogist, who gave the tuberculin\ntests is an employee of the State\nBoard of Health, which Board sent\nDr. Kilbourne at the request of\nthe Women's Clubs, and a physic\nian who is a member of the Assoc\niation, to give these tests in Car\nbon county. Appreciation of this\nservice to the Carbon County High\nSchool students should increase\nthe amount of the Seal Sale fund\nin Carbon County. Mrs. Field stat\ned that this was the result in Red\nLodge. Mrs. Spogen reported her\nincreased success as Chairman of\nthe Red Cross Roll Call in Carbon\nCounty last Fall, enrolling 603\nmembers and collecting $742.55\nwhich sum exceeds last year's by\n$140.00.\nP ARK THEATRE\nWEEKLY PROGRAM\nFri. Sat., Jan. 7-8. DOUBLE\nFEATURE: NO. 1 FRED STONE,\nDOROTHY MOORE in\n'QUICK\nMONEY\". Exciting human drama!\nNo. 2. BERT WHEELER, ROBT.\nWOOLSEY in \"HIGH FLYERS\"\nwith Lupe Velez. A drammer of\ntwo aeronuts that will split your\nfuselage! RAINBOW NIGHT SAT\nURDAY.\nCOMING! SUN. MON. TUES.,\nJan. 9-10-11. FREDRIC MARCH\nVs, CAROLE LOMBARD in\n\"NOTHING SACRE D\". The\nTECHNICOLOR comedy that will\nhave you rolling in the aisles.\nSCOOP! SINKING OF THE\n\"PANAY.\nWed. Thurs. Jan. 12-13. A\nGREAT musicial with a GREAT\ncast! \"52nd STREET\" with Ian\nHunter, Leo Carrillo, Pat Pater\nson, Kenny Baker, Sid Silvers,\nZazu Pitts. A good time will be\nhad by all. Also short subjects.\nRAINBOW NIGHT WEDNES\nDAY.\nFri. and Sat.,\u2014Jan., 14-15. The\nGREATEST football picture ever\nfilmed! ROBERT YOUNG, JAMES\nSTEWART and FLORENCE RICE\nin \"NAVY, BLUE and GOLD.\nTwo Annapolis Midshipmen dare\ndevils, scared to death over a girl\nThrilling drama and action on the\ngridiron! Also Musical Novelty\nand Donald Duck cartoon. RAIN\nBOW NIGHT SATURDAY.\nCOMING! SUN., MON., TUES.,\nJan. 16-17-18, THE TOPS OF MU\nSICALS is HERE AT LAST!\nNELSON EDDY, ELEANOR\nPOWELL, in \"ROSALIE.\" The\n\"King Of Song,\" in love with the\n\"Queen Of Taps!\" Eddy thrills\nyou as only he can..and Powell\ndoes her famous \"Drum Dance!\"\n\nEdgar Noses Out\nJoliet 27 To 26\nIn a slam-bang game that was\nthrilling all the way through, Ed\ngar nosed out Joliet's high school\nhoopsters at Edgar Wednesday\nnight, 27 to 26.\nJoliet pressed the winners from\nthe start and staged a last quarter\nrally that brought them within a\npoint of a tie. The score was 19\nto 12 for Edgar at half time.\nBolenske, with 9 points, and\nDavidson, with 7, led the victorious\nquint, while Grill and Danford\neach bagged 8 to keep the losers\nin the running.\nWALLUM'S\nSOLEMN\nCOLUMN\nBy EVERETT WALLUM\nTime Barges On\nDon't be mislead by the chaff in\nthe news. Don't be fed the literary\npap and subterfuge you'll find at\nevery hand! We gaze into our cry\nstal ball and tell you the signifi\ncant events of the past year.\nHere's our chronology for 1937:\nJan. 1\u2014\"oink,\nexhaust. \"Prrrulfowouzikkle,\nkledff,\" exhaust. (That's\narrrk,\nwhifff,\"\nsnar\njust\nsnores coming from people that\nslept it off).\nJan. 7.\u2014People finally sleep it\noff, according to official announce\nment made by city dignitaries.\nJan. 8\u2014D. W. Columbus steps\nout for a breath of morning air.\nHe inhales deeply, stops when he\nsees what looks like a feather\ndrifting lazily in the breeze. For\ngetting about breathing, D. W.\ngives chase while populace cheers.\nLast seen at eve, the athlete is\nseen going over hill near Roberts.\nJAN. 9\u2014FEATHER TURNS\nOUT TO BE FRAGMENT OF\nGAILY COLORED PETTICOAT,\nUNDERCOVER MEN REVEAL.\nCITY RETURNS TO HIBERNA\nTION.\nFeb. 2\u2014Groundhog appears:\nGail Nelson orders 2 lbs. pork\nsauage.\nFeb. 18\u2014'Doc Siegfriedt starts\nlimbering up the old soupbone for\nthe tourist season. Scans highway\nhopefully.\nFeb. 31\u2014(You dope, there isn't\nany Feb. 31\u2014Editor note) (The\nheck there isn't. Well, there is on\nmy calendar! I got at from Judge\nSanderson and he always sees to\nit a guy gets a couple extra days)\n\u2014Mike Hudak is seen chasing a\nrabbit. Mike is down! No, he's up\nagain. The Rabbit's down! and\nwhat nice down, too!\nMARCH 1\u2014MARCH COMES\nIN LIKE A LION.\u2014 ADV. SEEM\nALIVE ZOO.\nMarch 15\u2014Revelations that\nDutch Hartwig is playing marb\nles with the gang is brought out\nwhen kids squeal to officers that\nDutch refuses to \"knuckle down.\n\nMarch 16\u2014Testifying in court,\nDutch said dramatically that he\n\"did knuckle down,\" but that \"Emil\nDimich always pushes me when\nI shoot.\" County Attorney brands\nDutch as an old meanie, while\nhardened members of the jury sob,\nnecessitating recessing trial un\ntil next day. Crowd interest high.\nMARCH 30\u2014GEBO\nBOWLS\nAND HURTS FINGER. RUSHES\nHOME AND RETURNS WITH\nDIGIT SWATHED IN BAND\nAGES WHILE FEMME ONLOOK\nERS SHRIEK AND SWOON AT\nTHE SIGHT.\nApril 1\u2014A person laughs at this\ncolumn, Sent to insanity board for\nobservation. Identified as Everett\nWallum. Board's verdict:\nless, but a sad case.\n'harm\n\nApril 18\u2014Leland Newman says\nhe might let Jack Dempsey referee\na fight here if he'd shave and post\na bond.\nMay 1\u2014Smiling through his\ntears. Jack McFate bravely points\nout that there are only 242 days\nuntil he'll get more calendars. \"I\ndon't care a fig about the dates,\"\nhe sobbed, \"its the pictures.\"\nMay 21\u2014Gail Nelson opines he's\nnigh onto bald and that he thinks\nhe can stand off barbers until July\n3.\nJUNE 13 LEO SPOGEN\nCATCHES TROUT OVER 173\nPOUNDS (AND NO ONE WAS\nON THE SCALES BUT LEO AND\nTHE TROUT, EITHER).\nJuly 3\u2014'Gail looks sorrowfully\nupon shorn locks.\nJuly 28\u2014A courtroom sensation\nwas created when Dutch breaks\ndov\u00bbn and confesses he didn't\nknuckle down.\nAug. 14\u2014Marge Crutcher says\n\"Oh Fuzz!\" and shocked office\nforce at News Office bolts for door.\nThere being no bolts in door, all\nswoon.\nSept. 8\u2014School starts and Za\nputil says he doesn't feel well to\nday.\nS\nOCT. 18\u2014GAY '90S PROVE TO\nBE THE THIRSTY '30S.\nNov. 30\u2014Fbrty people wake up\nand ask \"what was it I et?\"\nDec. 31\u2014 E. B. Shelley first fire\nman to help put out steam at li\nbrary.\nHo hum McNewyear.","height":"22029","width":"16392"}}
